```

You have several options to change this icon:

1. **Modify the SVG path directly** - Change the `d` attribute in the path element to create a different icon shape.

2. **Replace with a completely new SVG** - Replace the entire SVG structure with a new one.

3. **Import an icon from a library** - Remove this function and import an icon from a library like Lucide or Heroicons:

   ```tsx
   import { ChevronDown } from "lucide-react"; // or any other icon

   // Then in your component:
   <Collapsible.Trigger className={styles.Trigger}>
       <ChevronDown className={styles.Icon} />
       Recovery keys
   </Collapsible.Trigger>
   ```

4. **Create a new icon component** - Create a different icon component and use it instead of `ChevronIcon`.

The icon is passed as a child to the `Collapsible.Trigger` component, so you can replace it with any SVG or icon component you prefer while maintaining the same CSS class (`styles.Icon`) for consistent styling.
If I were to change it with a minus sign made with css, that automatically rotates into a plus sign when the collapsible is closed.

Great idea! You can create a rotating plus/minus icon using CSS that transforms based on the open/closed state of the collapsible. Here's how to implement it:

First, modify your component:

```tsx
import * as React from "react";
import { Collapsible } from "@base-ui-components/react/collapsible";
import styles from "./Collapsible.module.css";

export default function ExampleCollapsible() {
    const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = React.useState(false);

    return (
        <Collapsible.Root 
            className={styles.Collapsible}
            open={isOpen}
            onOpenChange={setIsOpen}
        >
            <Collapsible.Trigger className={styles.Trigger}>
                <div className={`${styles.PlusMinusIcon} ${isOpen ? styles.open : ''}`}></div>
                Recovery keys
            </Collapsible.Trigger>
            <Collapsible.Panel className={styles.Panel}>
                <div className={styles.Content}>
                    <div>alien-bean-pasta</div>
                    <div>wild-irish-burrito</div>
                    <div>horse-battery-staple</div>
                </div>
            </Collapsible.Panel>
        </Collapsible.Root>
    );
}
```

Then, in your CSS module (Collapsible.module.css), add these styles:

```css
.PlusMinusIcon {
  position: relative;
  width: 14px;
  height: 14px;
  display: inline-block;
  transition: transform 0.3s ease;
}

/* Horizontal line (present in both plus and minus) */
.PlusMinusIcon::before {
  content: '';
  position: absolute;
  top: 50%;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
  height: 2px;
  background-color: currentColor;
  transform: translateY(-50%);
}

/* Vertical line (only visible in plus) */
.PlusMinusIcon::after {
  content: '';
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 50%;
  width: 2px;
  height: 100%;
  background-color: currentColor;
  transform: translateX(-50%);
  transition: transform 0.3s ease;
}

/* When open (minus), rotate the vertical line to make it invisible */
.PlusMinusIcon.open::after {
  transform: translateX(-50%) rotate(90deg) scaleX(0);
}
```

This implementation:

1. Replaces the SVG with a CSS-based icon that uses pseudo-elements
2. Creates a plus sign using two perpendicular lines
3. When the collapsible is open, it transforms the vertical line by rotating it and scaling it to zero width, effectively creating a minus sign
4. Uses smooth transitions for a nice animation effect between states

The key aspects:
- We track the open state with a React useState hook
- We apply a conditional class based on that state
- The CSS transforms handle the visual change between plus and minus

This gives you a clean, animated plus/minus icon that transforms based on the collapsible state, all using pure CSS.
I got this error: 

TypeError: useState only works in Client Components. Add the "use client" directive at the top of the file to use it. Read more: https://nextjs.org/docs/messages/react-client-hook-in-server-component


This error occurs because you're trying to use React's `useState` hook in a Server Component. In Next.js 13+, components are Server Components by default, and hooks like `useState` can only be used in Client Components.

To fix this issue, you need to add the `"use client"` directive at the top of your file. Here's the corrected version:

```tsx
"use client";

import * as React from "react";
import { Collapsible } from "@base-ui-components/react/collapsible";
import styles from "./Collapsible.module.css";

export default function ExampleCollapsible() {
    const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = React.useState(false);

    return (
        <Collapsible.Root 
            className={styles.Collapsible}
            open={isOpen}
            onOpenChange={setIsOpen}
        >
            <Collapsible.Trigger className={styles.Trigger}>
                <div className={`${styles.PlusMinusIcon} ${isOpen ? styles.open : ''}`}></div>
                Recovery keys
            </Collapsible.Trigger>
            <Collapsible.Panel className={styles.Panel}>
                <div className={styles.Content}>
                    <div>alien-bean-pasta</div>
                    <div>wild-irish-burrito</div>
                    <div>horse-battery-staple</div>
                </div>
            </Collapsible.Panel>
        </Collapsible.Root>
    );
}
```

The `"use client"` directive must be placed as the first line in your file (even before imports) to mark this component as a Client Component. This tells Next.js that this component (and any components imported into it) should be rendered on the client side, where React hooks like `useState` can be used.

This is part of Next.js's hybrid rendering model, which enables you to choose between Server and Client Components to optimize performance and user experience.

Where would I go to change the global font size in base ui?
To change the global font size in a Base UI application, you typically need to modify your global CSS variables or theme configuration. Base UI, like many modern UI frameworks, uses a theming system based on CSS variables for consistent styling.

Here are the main approaches to change global font size:

### 1. Modify Global CSS Variables

Create or update your global CSS file (often in `/styles/globals.css` or similar):

```css
:root {
  /* Base font size - this affects the entire application */
  font-size: 16px; /* Change this to your desired base size */

  /* If Base UI uses specific font size variables */
  --base-font-size-xs: 0.75rem;
  --base-font-size-sm: 0.875rem;
  --base-font-size-md: 1rem;
  --base-font-size-lg: 1.125rem;
  --base-font-size-xl: 1.25rem;
  --base-font-size-2xl: 1.5rem;
  /* Add more size variables as needed */
}
```

### 2. Using Tailwind CSS (if your Base UI implementation uses Tailwind)

If your Base UI setup uses Tailwind CSS, modify the `tailwind.config.js` file:

```js
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      fontSize: {
        'xs': '0.75rem',
        'sm': '0.875rem',
        'base': '1rem',    // Change this for your base font size
        'lg': '1.125rem',
        'xl': '1.25rem',
        '2xl': '1.5rem',
        // Add more custom sizes as needed
      },
    },
  },
  // Other config options...
}
```

### 3. Through a ThemeProvider

If Base UI uses a ThemeProvider component, you can set font sizes through the theme prop:

```tsx
// In _app.tsx or your root layout component
import { ThemeProvider } from '@your-base-ui/theme';

const myTheme = {
  typography: {
    fontSize: {
      base: '16px',
      small: '14px',
      large: '18px',
      // other font sizes
    }
  }
  // other theme properties
};

function MyApp({ Component, pageProps }) {
  return (
    <ThemeProvider theme={myTheme}>
      <Component {...pageProps} />
    </ThemeProvider>
  );
}
```

### 4. Using Next.js App Router

If you're using Next.js App Router, you might set global styles in your root layout:

```tsx
// app/layout.tsx
import './globals.css'; // Contains your global font size settings

export default function RootLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>{children}</body>
    </html>
  );
}
```

