How would I go about to change the default font family for the entire application? I want to run Roboto as my main font.
Perfect! Now that we've found where the font variables are set up, changing to Roboto is straightforward. Here's how to update your `layout.tsx` file to use Roboto as your main font:

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from "next";
import { Roboto, Roboto_Mono } from "next/font/google";
import "./globals.css";

// Replace Geist with Roboto
const roboto = Roboto({
  variable: "--font-geist-sans", // Keep the same variable name for compatibility
  subsets: ["latin"],
  weight: ["400", "500", "700"], // Add the weights you need
  display: "swap",
});

// Replace Geist_Mono with Roboto_Mono or keep a monospace font of your choice
const robotoMono = Roboto_Mono({
  variable: "--font-geist-mono", // Keep the same variable name for compatibility
  subsets: ["latin"],
  weight: ["400", "500", "700"], // Add the weights you need
  display: "swap",
});

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: "Create Next App",
  description: "Generated by create next app",
};

export default function RootLayout({
  children,
}: Readonly<{
  children: React.ReactNode;
}>) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body className={`${roboto.variable} ${robotoMono.variable}`}>
        {children}
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```

**Key changes:**

1. Import `Roboto` and `Roboto_Mono` from `next/font/google` instead of Geist
2. Configure the Roboto font with your preferred weights
3. Keep the same variable names (`--font-geist-sans` and `--font-geist-mono`) so you don't have to update all CSS references
4. Apply the new font variables to the body element

**Important notes:**

1. By maintaining the same CSS variable names (`--font-geist-sans`), you don't need to update all your CSS files that reference these variables.

2. If you prefer to rename the variables to match the new fonts (which is cleaner semantically), you could change them to:
   ```tsx
   const roboto = Roboto({
     variable: "--font-roboto", // New name
     // other options
   });

   const robotoMono = Roboto_Mono({
     variable: "--font-roboto-mono", // New name
     // other options
   });
   ```

   But then you'd need to update all CSS files that reference the old variable names to use the new ones.

3. Be sure to choose the weights you need for your application. The example includes 400 (regular), 500 (medium), and 700 (bold).

This change will apply Roboto as your main font throughout the entire application while maintaining compatibility with your existing CSS.

